Introduction

This is an analysis on a pressing issue in the continent of Africa: Maternal Mortality. We will analyse the figures of the decline of maternal mortality from 2020 to 2000. This will be done through the visualisations seen below. We will examine different factors that can contribute to high numbers of maternal mortality and that is GDP per capita. This analysis will concur if low levels of GDP correlate to high levels of maternal mortality.

file_path = '/content/drive/My Drive/unicef-data/unicef_indicator_1.csv'
indicator_1 = pd.read_csv(file_path)
file_path = '/content/drive/My Drive/unicef-data/unicef_indicator_2.csv'
indicator_2 = pd.read_csv(file_path)
file_path = '/content/drive/My Drive/unicef-data/unicef_metadata.csv'
metadata = pd.read_csv(file_path)
Code 
import pandas as pd
maternal_mortality_in_indicator_2 = indicator_2[indicator_2['indicator'].str.contains('maternal', case=False, na=False)]
maternal_mortality_data_filtered = maternal_mortality_in_indicator_2[maternal_mortality_in_indicator_2['time_period'] >= 2000]
african_countries = [
    'DZA', 'AGO', 'BWA', 'BFA', 'BDI', 'CMR', 'CPV', 'CAF', 'TCD', 'COM', 'COD', 'COG', 'DJI', 'EGY',
    'GNQ', 'ERI', 'SWZ', 'ETH', 'GAB', 'GMB', 'GHA', 'GIN', 'GNB', 'CIV', 'KEN', 'LSO', 'LBR', 'LBY',
    'MDG', 'MWI', 'MRT', 'MUS', 'MOZ', 'NAM', 'NER', 'NGA', 'RWA', 'STP', 'SEN', 'SYC', 'SLE', 'SOM',
    'ZAF', 'SSD', 'SDN', 'TGO', 'TUN', 'UGA', 'TZA', 'ZMB', 'ZWE'
]
african_maternal_mortality = maternal_mortality_data_filtered[maternal_mortality_data_filtered['alpha_3_code'].isin(african_countries)]
africa_avg_mortality = african_maternal_mortality.groupby('time_period')['obs_value'].mean().reset_index()
africa_avg_mortality['country'] = 'Africa'
global_avg_mortality = maternal_mortality_data_filtered.groupby('time_period')['obs_value'].mean().reset_index()
global_avg_mortality['country'] = 'Global'
combined_data = pd.concat([africa_avg_mortality[['time_period', 'obs_value', 'country']],
                           global_avg_mortality[['time_period', 'obs_value', 'country']]],
                          ignore_index=True)

Maternal Mortality: Africa vs Global Average

The time series chart below highlights the harsh reality of the high levels of mortality in Africa compared to the rest of the world. Although the ratio in Africa has significantly improved, dropping by almost 300 deaths in 20 years, the current number is still concerning. The data from 2020 highlights that many African countries continue to face challenges such as:

  • limited healthcare infrastructure
  • inadequate access to skilled healthcare professionals
  • socio-economic barriers

The graph shows great progress in reducing the numbers, but they are not nearly as low as they should be. International health organisations and national governments need to implement more comprehensive maternal health programs in African regions. Targeted interventions are needed in Africa to improve maternal healthcare access, reduce preventable deaths, and work toward achieving the United Nations Sustainable Development Goal of reducing maternal mortality.

Code 
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
sns.set(style="whitegrid")
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.lineplot(data=combined_data, x='time_period', y='obs_value', hue='country', marker="o")
plt.title("Maternal Mortality Ratio: Africa vs Global Average (2000-2020)", fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel("Year", fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel("Maternal Mortality Ratio (per 100,000 live births)", fontsize=12)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)

plt.annotate(f"Start: {africa_avg_mortality['obs_value'].iloc[0]:.2f}",
             xy=(2000, africa_avg_mortality['obs_value'].iloc[0]),
             xytext=(2000, africa_avg_mortality['obs_value'].iloc[0]+50),
             arrowprops=dict(facecolor='blue', arrowstyle='->'),
             fontsize=12, color='blue')
plt.annotate(f"End: {africa_avg_mortality['obs_value'].iloc[-1]:.2f}",
             xy=(2020, africa_avg_mortality['obs_value'].iloc[-1]),
             xytext=(2020, africa_avg_mortality['obs_value'].iloc[-1]+50),
             arrowprops=dict(facecolor='blue', arrowstyle='->'),
             fontsize=12, color='blue')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Maternal Mortality vs GDP per Capita

The scatter plot below shows the direct correlation between the number of maternal mortality in a country alongside its GDP per Capita for the year. The plot reveals a negative correlation, suggesting that higher GDP per capita is generally associated with lower maternal mortality rates in African countries. The regression line highlights the overall trend, showing that countries with wealthier economies tend to have better healthcare systems, which can lead to improved maternal health outcomes. There are many outliers amongst the data suggesting the issue of maternal mortality has other determinants apart from GDP. The complexity of maternal health needs to be addressed through improving healthcare access and quality in countries with both low and medium GDP per Capita.

Code 
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
scatter_data_gdp = pd.merge(
    african_maternal_mortality[['country', 'time_period', 'obs_value']],
    metadata[['country', 'GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)']],
    on='country', how='inner'
)
scatter_data_gdp_2020 = scatter_data_gdp[scatter_data_gdp['time_period'] == 2020]
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.regplot(
    x='GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)',
    y='obs_value',
    data=scatter_data_gdp_2020,
    scatter_kws={'color': 'blue', 's': 50, 'alpha': 0.5},
    line_kws={'color': 'red', 'lw': 2},
    robust=True,
)
plt.title("Scatterplot of Maternal Mortality vs GDP per Capita (2020)", fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel("GDP per Capita (constant 2015 US$)", fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel("Maternal Mortality Ratio (per 100,000 live births)", fontsize=12)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

World Map

Below showcases the figures of maternal mortality worldwide in 2000 and 2020. From the analysis of the maps, we can see a clear disparity between Africa and other continents. Red highlights areas that have low maternal mortality and blue highlights high levels, with yellow being the middle. In 2000 and 2020, most countries outside of Africa had low levels of mortality, with Africa being the only continent to have higher levels, with yellow and blue throughout the continent. The comparison shows praise to areas outside of Africa in dealing with maternal mortality. Unfortunately for Africa, many countries’ infrastructure in place is not adequate to deal with multiple different health problems, and this is seen with the high numbers of maternal mortality. The bar charts below will highlight the countries with the highest and lowest maternal mortality in Africa.

Code 
import geopandas as gpd
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
shapefile_path = '/content/drive/MyDrive/countries/extracted_shapefile/ne_110m_admin_0_countries.shp'
world = gpd.read_file(shapefile_path)
world_maternal_mortality_2020 = maternal_mortality_data_filtered[maternal_mortality_data_filtered['time_period'] == 2020]
world_map_data_2020 = world.set_index('SOV_A3').join(world_maternal_mortality_2020.set_index('alpha_3_code')['obs_value'])
world_map_data_2020['obs_value'] = world_map_data_2020['obs_value'].fillna(world_map_data_2020['obs_value'].mean())  # or use dropna() if preferred
sorted_world_2020 = world_map_data_2020.sort_values(by='obs_value', ascending=False)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(20, 12))
world_map_data_2020.plot(column='obs_value', ax=ax, legend=True,
                         legend_kwds={'label': "Maternal Mortality Ratio (per 100,000 live births)",
                                      'orientation': "horizontal", 'pad': 0.1},
                         cmap='RdYlBu')
ax.grid(False)
plt.title("Maternal Mortality in the World (2020)", fontsize=20, weight='bold')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Top 10 Maternal Mortality Countries

Below we can see the countries with the 10 best and worst figures regarding maternal mortality in Africa. The graphs compare the difference between 2000 and 2020 and how the 20 years has affected the countries at the top and bottom. South Sudan has the highest mortality numbers in both years, which could be closely attributed to South Sudan being labelled one of the poorest countries in the world. This links well with our analysis of the effect of GDP on the figures. Although its numbers have dropped by almost 400, the figures are still astronomically high. Many of the other countries in the top 10 suffer from low GDP but one country stands out, which is Nigeria whose economy isn’t bad in comparison to the other countries on the list. This can be attributed to reduced access to health services and highlights the gap between rich and poor which is a major issue in Nigeria at this moment.

Code 
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
maternal_mortality_2020 = maternal_mortality_data_filtered[maternal_mortality_data_filtered['time_period'] == 2020]
top_10_2020 = maternal_mortality_2020.sort_values(by='obs_value', ascending=False).head(10)
maternal_mortality_2000 = maternal_mortality_data_filtered[maternal_mortality_data_filtered['time_period'] == 2000]
top_10_2000 = maternal_mortality_2000.sort_values(by='obs_value', ascending=False).head(10)
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
bars_2020 = plt.barh(top_10_2020['country'], top_10_2020['obs_value'], color='darkred')
for i, bar in enumerate(bars_2020):
    plt.text(bar.get_width() + 2, bar.get_y() + bar.get_height() / 2, f'{top_10_2020["obs_value"].iloc[i]:.2f}',
             va='center', fontsize=12, color='black')

plt.xlabel('Maternal Mortality Ratio (per 100,000 live births)', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Country', fontsize=12)
plt.title('Top 10 African Countries by Maternal Mortality (2020)', fontsize=16, weight='bold')
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
bars_2000 = plt.barh(top_10_2000['country'], top_10_2000['obs_value'], color='darkred')
for i, bar in enumerate(bars_2000):
    plt.text(bar.get_width() + 2, bar.get_y() + bar.get_height() / 2, f'{top_10_2000["obs_value"].iloc[i]:.2f}',
             va='center', fontsize=12, color='black')

plt.xlabel('Maternal Mortality Ratio (per 100,000 live births)', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Country', fontsize=12)
plt.title('Top 10 African Countries by Maternal Mortality (2000)', fontsize=16, weight='bold')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
plt.show()

Bottom 10 Maternal Mortality Countries

Below highlights the countries with the lowest maternal mortality per 100,000 births. Seychelles has remained top of the list throughout the years. Seychelles has a population of around 100,000 people, so the factor of fewer population can provide more care and better facilities for residents to give birth to their children. Other countries in the list, such as Egypt, Algeria, and South Africa, are no surprises on the list as they have some of the highest GDP in the whole of Africa, which can correlate to better facilities and health infrastructure in these countries.

Conclusion

The current data shows a relationship between Maternal Mortality and GDP per Capita. Most countries align with the consensus of low GDP = high maternal mortality, although there are some outliers, such as Nigeria and Mozambique. Although GDP is not a direct answer to solving maternal mortality, it helps address other issues that poorer countries are incapable of addressing. From 2000 to 2020, we can see a consistent drop in maternal mortality across the continent, which is great progress, but the numbers are still far too high to claim the problem is fixed. Many of the countries who have poor numbers are generally areas that are conflict-affected or fragile. Prevention strategies should be integrated into humanitarian response, and maternal health should also be prioritised in climate adaptation plans to address these emerging threats that are affecting the well-being of pregnant women. With the figures presented, we can see a generally strong connection between the two variables. Unfortunately, the comparison between the two is not constant and predictable; therefore, we can infer that high GDP is crucial to reducing maternal mortality in Africa, but other factors and variables can help tackle the poor statistics around quality and infrastructure in the corresponding healthcare systems.
